   <text>
      <front>
         <p>1876 December 4: to McLean<note xml:id="ftn2-280" place="foot" n="280"> ATL Object #1000198 from MS-Papers-0032-0222.</note>
         </p>
      </front>
      <body>
         <p rend="end">Napier</p>
         <p rend="end">Decr. 4/76</p>
         <p>My Dear Sir Donald McLean </p>
         <p>I only returned to Napier by late train on Saturday from 40 m. Bush, &amp;c.—but I had heard inland of your arrival here &amp; of your being so <hi rend="italic">very much better</hi>,—which I was glad to hear.<note xml:id="ftn2-281" place="foot" n="281"> McLean died a month later: 5 January 1877.</note>
         </p>
         <p>I must be <hi rend="italic">very </hi>busy every school day with the schools between this &amp; vacation, but I shall have <hi rend="italic">Saturdays</hi> at command, &amp; will do myself the honour &amp; pleasure of calling on you next Saturday—should the weather prove favourable, and you disengaged.</p>
         <p>Hoping you may rapidly rally—and once more be yourself again—I am</p>
         <p>My Dear Donald</p>
         <p>Yours truly</p>
         <p>
            <hi rend="underline">W. Colenso</hi>.</p>
      </body>
   </text>
